## Why This Is Asked
This question tests understanding of per-tenant data isolation, retention controls, and safe data purging in a live streaming system. It requires concrete API shape, data model decisions, and a practical testing strategy suitable for beginners while exposing real trade-offs.

## Key Concepts
- Tenant-scoped retention policy and TTL
- Message metadata and tombstone semantics for replay
- Purge safety relative to consumer offsets
- Canary-based testing and end-to-end validation

## Code Example
```javascript
// Pseudo: set TTL for a tenant-topic
async function setTTL(tenantId, topic, ttlMs) {
  // persist TTL in config store per tenant-topic
  await configStore.set(`/tenants/${tenantId}/topics/${topic}/ttl`, ttlMs);
}

// Pseudo: purge loop (simplified)
function purgeOldMessages(tenantId, topic) {
  const ttlMs = configStore.get(`/tenants/${tenantId}/topics/${topic}/ttl`);
  const cutoff = Date.now() - ttlMs;
  for (const msg of storage.scan(tenantId, topic)) {
    if (msg.timestamp < cutoff) {
      storage.delete(msg.id);
      // emit tombstone to preserve replay semantics
      storage.appendTombstone({ tenantId, topic, id: msg.id });
    }
  }
}
```

## Follow-up Questions
- How would you handle TTL changes mid-flight without losing data consistency?
- How do you verify no live consumers are affected during purge windows?

