## Why This Is Asked
Tests real-time handling of dynamic policies, data privacy, and end-to-end guarantees in KCNA.

## Key Concepts
- Dynamic per-tenant policy loading from a KCNA topic
- Real-time cache updates with atomic policy changes
- Data redaction strategies (none, partial, full)
- Idempotent sinks and at-least-once guarantees
- Testing under policy updates and message reordering

## Code Example
```javascript
function redact(customer, level) {
  if (level === 'full') return { name: null, email: null, card: null };
  if (level === 'partial') {
    const maskedCard = customer.card.replace(/\d(?=\d{4})/g, '*');
    const maskedEmail = customer.email.replace(/([^@]{1,2})[^@]*(@.*)/, (m, p1, p2) => p1[0] + '**' + p2);
    return { ...customer, card: maskedCard, email: maskedEmail };
  }
  return customer;
}
```

## Why This Is Asked
This question tests understanding of runtime configurability, deduplication logic, and offset management—skills essential for building robust streaming pipelines in production systems.

## Key Concepts
- **Runtime config updates**: Using a dedicated configuration topic to dynamically control sink behavior
- **Per-message deduplication**: Maintaining deduplication state across message processing
- **Toggle behavior**: Safely switching deduplication on/off without losing in-flight messages
- **At-least-once semantics**: Ensuring offsets commit even when deduplication is bypassed
- **Graceful state management**: Handling the transition between dedup-enabled and disabled modes

## Code Example
```javascript
class RuntimeConfig {
  constructor() { this.disableDedup = false; }

  apply(event) {
    if (typeof event.disableDedup === 'boolean') {
      this.disableDedup = event.disableDedup;
    }
  }
}
```

## Follow-up Questions
- How would you test race conditions between config updates and incoming messages?
- What happens to deduplication state when the connector restarts?
- How would you implement this using Kafka Streams instead of a sink connector?
